Part I - PISA 2018 Database¶

by Nguyen Thi Thuy¶

Introduction¶

The 2018 PISA School Dataset was constructed and organized into SAS and SPSS files. PISA, an acronym for "Programme for International Student Assessment," is a triennial assessment covering reading, mathematics, and science literacy that is taken by 15 year-old students. In 2018, PISA involved 79 countries and 600,000+ students worldwide.

In this project, I'm going to evaluate the key factors affecting students' overall literacy.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The data set includes 612004 rows and 34 columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I would like to assess evaluate the key factors affecting students' overall literacy, therefore the students' maths, science, reading, time spent at home and parents education, accupation are the main features of interest in the dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

CNT - Country (Categorical) 
OECD - Is OECD or not (Categorical) 
GRADE - Student Grade out of 100 (Quantitative) 
PV1MATH, PV2MATH, PV3MATH, PV4MATH, PV5MATH, 
PV1SCIE, PV2SCIE, PV3SCIE, PV4SCIE, PV5SCIE, 
PV1READ, PV2READ, PV3READ, PV4READ, PV5READ 
ST001D01T - Gender (Categorical) 
IC010Q01TA to IC010Q07TA - computer, internet, cellphone at home 
IC08Q08 - Obtain practical information from the Internet (Categorical) 
ST225Q01HA - Acculturation: Mother Immigrant (Filter) (Categorical) 
HISCED - Highest educational level of parents (Categorical) 
HISEI - Highest parental occupational status (Quantitative) 
FISCED - Educational level of father (ISCED) (Categorical) 
PARED - Highest parental education in years (Quantitative) 
REPEAT - Grade Repetition (class repeated) (Categorical)

Creating new variables¶

We need to create 3 variables each of which will be created from average of 5 plausible variables found in each of mathematical, scientific, reading literacy, and another one will be composed of the average of the 3 previously created variables as shown below.

The following 3 variables that will be created are called:

Avg_Math: Average of Maths
Avg_Scientific: Average of Scientific
Avg_Reading: Average of Reading
Overall_Literacy: Average of the 3 previously variables
In [24]:
df_pisa['Avg_Math'] = df_pisa[['PV1MATH','PV2MATH','PV3MATH', 'PV4MATH', 'PV5MATH']].mean(axis=1)
df_pisa['Avg_Scientific'] = df_pisa[['PV1SCIE','PV2SCIE','PV3SCIE','PV4SCIE','PV5SCIE']].mean(axis=1)
df_pisa['Avg_Reading'] = df_pisa[['PV1READ','PV2READ','PV3READ', 'PV4READ', 'PV5READ']].mean(axis=1)
In [25]:
df_pisa['Overall_Literacy'] = df_pisa[['Avg_Math', 'Avg_Scientific','Avg_Reading']].mean(axis=1)

From the chart we can see that, China has the biggist number of students who have the highest overall literacy compared to other nations. The second one is Singapore and the third one is Macao.

Relationship between Grade and Overall Literacy¶

We can see that, the Overall_Literacy is affected by the internet connection. The Overall_Literacy is highest at student group that they use once or twice a month and lowest at student group that they use everyday.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Highest Parental Occupational Status vs Overall Literacy and Class Repeated¶

In [41]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df_pisa, hue = 'Class_repeated', height = 12)
g.map(plt.scatter, 'Highest_parental_occu_status', 'Overall_Literacy', alpha=1)
plt.title("Parent's Highest Occupational Status and its effect on Overall Literacy of Students and Repeated Class")
plt.xlabel('Highest Parental Occupational Status')
plt.ylabel('Overall Literacy')
g.add_legend(title ='Class Repeated?');
plt.rcParams.update({'font.size': 16});

As the Parents' occupational status increase so does the student's overall literacy, with that less and less students have repeated a class. The right side of the plot has majority of students who did not repeat a class whereas, as the parents' occupational status decrease so does the student's overall literacy, with that more and more students repeated a grade.

Highest Parental Occupational Status affects Overall Literacy and Grade¶

In [31]:
plt.figure(figsize = [24, 16])
plt.scatter(data = df_pisa, x = 'Highest_parental_occu_status', y = 'Overall_Literacy', c = 'Grade',
            cmap = 'icefire_r', alpha=1)
plt.title("Parent's Highest Occupational Status and its effect on Overall Literacy of Students and Grade")
plt.xlabel('Highest Parental Occupational Status')
plt.ylabel('Overall Literacy')
plt.colorbar(label = 'Grade');

We can see that the student's overall literacy increase as the Parents' occupational status increase. The right side of the plot has majority of students who are in the countrys modal grade if not above the modal grade. Whereas, as the parents' occupational status decrease so does the student's overall literacy, with that more and more students are below the modal grade.

Internet Connection affects Class Repeated and Overall Literacy¶

In [61]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df_pisa, col = 'Internet_Connection', col_wrap=2, height = 5)
g.map(sb.boxplot, 'Class_repeated', 'Overall_Literacy', color='darkred');
g.axes[0].set_title("No");
g.axes[1].set_title("Yes, but I don't use it");
g.axes[2].set_title("Yes, and I use it");
g.axes[3].set_title("Once or twice a month");
g.axes[4].set_title("Once or twice a week");

An observation found here is that students had repeated a grade and used internet connection had a higher overall literacy compared to students who repeated or not repeated a class and they either had no internet connection or they had internet connection but didnt use it.

Conclusions¶

After explorating the dataset, I find some key points as follows:

  1. For the Grade Distribution

The data seems normally distributed with the peak at 0.0 interval and there are no outliers as the data is tidy.

  1. For the Overall literacy

The average score is around 500 in all Maths, Science and reading.

  1. The Country where has the highest Overall Literacy

China has the biggist number of students who have the highest overall literacy compared to other nations. The second one is Singapore and the third one is Macao.

  1. Relationship between Internet connection and Overall Literacy

The Overall_Literacy is affected by the internet connection. The Overall_Literacy is highest at student group that they use once or twice a month and lowest at student group that they use everyday.

  1. Highest Parental Occupational Status affect Overall Literacy and Class Repeated

As the Parents' occupational status increase so does the student's overall literacy, with that less and less students have repeated a class. The right side of the plot has majority of students who did not repeat a class whereas, as the parents' occupational status decrease so does the student's overall literacy, with that more and more students repeated a grade.

  1. Internet Connection affects Class Repeated and Overall Literacy

An observation found here is that students had repeated a grade and used internet connection had a higher overall literacy compared to students who repeated or not repeated a class and they either had no internet connection or they had internet connection but didnt use it.
